And.name: Andromeda
And.description: A celestial portrayal of the mythical Greek princess chained to a rock as a sacrifice, immortalized among the stars. Her story of peril and rescue by Perseus is captured in this constellation's twinkling outline.

Ant.name: Antlia
Ant.description: A constellation representing an air pump, symbolizing scientific curiosity and the mechanical innovations of astronomical exploration.

Aps.name: Apus
Aps.description: A constellation depicting a bird of paradise from the southern skies, bringing exotic beauty to the celestial landscape.

Aql.name: Aquila
Aql.description: The majestic eagle constellation, traditionally associated with Zeus, soars across the night sky as a symbol of power and divine messenger.

Aqr.name: Aquarius
Aqr.description: A celestial water bearer pouring from a cosmic jug, representing the flow of life and the mystical qualities of water in ancient mythology.

Ara.name: Ara
Ara.description: An altar constellation where the gods would swear their most solemn oaths before battling the Titans, representing divine commitment and sacred ritual.

Ari.name: Aries
Ari.description: Commemorating the legendary golden-fleeced ram from Greek mythology, this constellation tells the tale of heroic quests and magical transformation.

Aur.name: Auriga
Aur.description: A celestial charioteer navigating the heavens, capturing the spirit of ancient Greek mythological heroes and their mastery of transportation.

Boo.name: BoÃ¶tes
Boo.description: The celestial herdsman following the Great Bear across the night sky, representing pastoral life and the eternal movement of celestial bodies.

CMa.name: Canis Major
CMa.description: Orion's larger hunting dog, home to the brilliant star Sirius, the brightest star in our night sky.

CMi.name: Canis Minor
CMi.description: Orion's smaller hunting dog, featuring the prominent star Procyon, completing the mythological hunting pack.

CVn.name: Canes Venatici
CVn.description: The hunting dogs of BoÃ¶tes, faithfully accompanying the herdsman through the celestial wilderness.

Cae.name: Caelum
Cae.description: A constellation shaped like a sculptor's chisel, honoring the artistry and precision of craftsmanship.

Cam.name: Camelopardalis
Cam.description: A constellation depicting a giraffe, bringing the wonder of exotic wildlife to the star-studded canvas of the night sky.

Cap.name: Capricornus
Cap.description: A mythical sea-goat with a goat's head and a fish's tail, bridging the realms of land and sea in a single fantastical creature.

Car.name: Carina
Car.description: Representing the keel of the mythical ship Argo Navis, this constellation speaks to maritime adventure and legendary voyages.

Cas.name: Cassiopeia
Cas.description: A constellation depicting the vain queen from Greek mythology, eternally spinning in the night sky as punishment for her pride.

Cen.name: Centaurus
Cen.description: A majestic representation of the mythical centaur - half-man, half-horse - embodying the complex nature of wisdom and wildness.

Cep.name: Cepheus
Cep.description: The king of mythology, husband to Cassiopeia, ruling over his celestial domain.

Cet.name: Cetus
Cet.description: The sea monster from Greek mythology that was sent to devour Andromeda, immortalized in the starry expanse.

Cha.name: Chamaeleon
Cha.description: A constellation celebrating the remarkable adaptability of the chameleon, blending into the cosmic landscape.

Cir.name: Circinus
Cir.description: Shaped like a geometrical drawing compass, this constellation represents precision and mathematical beauty.

Cnc.name: Cancer
Cnc.description: Commemorating the crab that bit Hercules during his legendary battle with the Hydra, this constellation tells a small but significant moment in mythological heroism.

Col.name: Columba
Col.description: Commemorating Noah's dove carrying an olive branch, symbolizing hope and peace.

Com.name: Coma Berenices
Com.description: A constellation representing the cut hair of Queen Berenice II, transformed into a celestial memorial.

CrA.name: Corona Australis
CrA.description: The southern crown worn by the centaur Sagittarius, a celestial decoration of mythological royalty.

CrB.name: Corona Borealis
CrB.description: The crown given to Ariadne by Dionysus, a symbol of love and divine gifting.

Crt.name: Crater
Crt.description: The cup of Apollo, associated with the mythological crow, representing divine libation and storytelling.

Cru.name: Crux
Cru.description: The Southern Cross, a prominent constellation of the southern skies, guiding travelers and holding deep cultural significance.

Crv.name: Corvus
Crv.description: A crow sent by Apollo to fetch water, immortalized in the stellar narrative of Greek mythology.

Cyg.name: Cygnus
Cyg.description: A swan representing Zeus in his transformative mythology, gliding majestically across the celestial river.

Del.name: Delphinus
Del.description: A dolphin that helped Poseidon find his bride, symbolizing assistance and divine intervention.

Dor.name: Dorado
Dor.description: A constellation representing a dolphinfish or goldfish, adding aquatic wonder to the night sky.

Dra.name: Draco
Dra.description: The dragon guarding the golden apples in Greek mythology, a symbol of protection and mythical treasure.

Equ.name: Equuleus
Equ.description: Either the foal of Mercury or part of the horse Pegasus, representing youthful potential and divine companionship.

Eri.name: Eridanus
Eri.description: A river constellation associated with Phaethon's legendary fall, embodying the drama of mythological storytelling.

For.name: Fornax
For.description: A constellation representing a scientific furnace, symbolizing human curiosity and the quest for knowledge.

Gem.name: Gemini
Gem.description: The twins Castor and Pollux, immortalized in the stars, representing brotherhood and mythological heroism.

Gru.name: Grus
Gru.description: A crane constellation, bringing the grace of avian life to the celestial sphere.

Her.name: Hercules
Her.description: Commemorating the legendary hero, representing strength, courage, and mythological achievement.

Hor.name: Horologium
Hor.description: A pendulum clock constellation, marking the passage of cosmic time.

Hya.name: Hydra
Hya.description: The multi-headed water snake killed by Hercules, a testament to heroic struggle.

Hyi.name: Hydrus
Hyi.description: Another water snake constellation, adding aquatic mystery to the night sky.

Ind.name: Indus
Ind.description: Representing Native Americans, a constellation celebrating cultural diversity and human connection.

LMi.name: Leo Minor
LMi.description: A smaller lion constellation, adding nuance to the leonine celestial presence.

Lac.name: Lacerta
Lac.description: A lizard constellation, bringing the subtle beauty of small creatures to the stellar landscape.

Leo.name: Leo
Leo.description: The Nemean lion slain by Hercules, a symbol of ferocity and legendary conquest.

Lep.name: Lepus
Lep.description: A hare being chased by Orion the hunter, capturing the dynamic of predator and prey.

Lib.name: Libra
Lib.description: The scales of justice, associated with the goddess Astraea, representing balance and moral order.

Lup.name: Lupus
Lup.description: A wolf being killed by the centaur Centaurus, dramatizing mythological conflict.

Lyn.name: Lynx
Lyn.description: A faint lynx constellation, embodying stealth and subtle presence.

Lyr.name: Lyra
Lyr.description: The lyre of Orpheus, representing musical harmony and mythological artistry.

Men.name: Mensa
Men.description: A constellation named after a table mountain in South Africa, connecting celestial and terrestrial landscapes.

Mic.name: Microscopium
Mic.description: A microscope constellation, symbolizing scientific exploration and the revelation of hidden worlds.

Mon.name: Monoceros
Mon.description: A unicorn constellation, bringing mythical magic to the night sky.

Mus.name: Musca
Mus.description: A fly constellation, demonstrating that even the smallest creatures have a place among the stars.

Nor.name: Norma
Nor.description: A carpenter's square constellation, representing precision and craftsmanship.

Oct.name: Octans
Oct.description: An octant navigation instrument constellation, guiding sailors and explorers.

Oph.name: Ophiuchus
Oph.description: The serpent bearer, a healer from Greek mythology, holding a serpent and symbolizing medical wisdom.

Ori.name: Orion
Ori.description: The legendary hunter of Greek mythology, one of the most recognizable constellations in the night sky.

Pav.name: Pavo
Pav.description: A peacock constellation, bringing regal beauty and ornate display to the celestial realm.

Peg.name: Pegasus
Peg.description: The winged horse from Greek mythology, symbolizing freedom and divine inspiration.

Per.name: Perseus
Per.description: The hero who rescued Andromeda, immortalized as a constellation of heroism and rescue.

Phe.name: Phoenix
Phe.description: The mythical bird that rises from its own ashes, representing renewal and eternal hope.

Pic.name: Pictor
Pic.description: An easel constellation, celebrating artistic creation and human creativity.

PsA.name: Piscis Austrinus
PsA.description: The southern fish, drinking water poured by Aquarius, connecting celestial elements.

Psc.name: Pisces
Psc.description: Two fish tied together, representing Venus and Cupid in mythological transformation.

Pup.name: Puppis
Pup.description: The stern of the ship Argo Navis, continuing the maritime mythology in the stars.

Pyx.name: Pyxis
Pyx.description: A mariner's compass constellation, guiding travelers through celestial and earthly journeys.

Ret.name: Reticulum
Ret.description: A net used by astronomers to measure star positions, representing scientific precision.

Scl.name: Sculptor
Scl.description: A sculptor's studio constellation, celebrating artistic creation.

Sco.name: Scorpius
Sco.description: The scorpion that killed Orion, a constellation of mythological revenge.

Sct.name: Scutum
Sct.description: A shield constellation, representing protection and defensive strength.

Ser.name: Serpens
Ser.description: A serpent held by Ophiuchus, divided into two parts, symbolizing complexity and duality.

Sex.name: Sextans
Sex.description: A sextant constellation, a tool of navigation and exploration.

Sge.name: Sagitta
Sge.description: An arrow constellation, possibly shot by Sagittarius or Hercules, symbolizing precision and power.

Sgr.name: Sagittarius
Sgr.description: A centaur archer from mythology, drawing his bow across the night sky.

Tau.name: Taurus
Tau.description: The bull from Greek mythology, possibly Zeus in disguise, representing strength and divine transformation.

Tel.name: Telescopium
Tel.description: A telescope constellation, symbolizing human curiosity and the expansion of knowledge.

TrA.name: Triangulum Australe
TrA.description: A surveyor's level constellation, representing precision and measurement.

Tri.name: Triangulum
Tri.description: A triangle representing the Nile delta or Sicily, connecting celestial geometry to earthly landscapes.

Tuc.name: Tucana
Tuc.description: A toucan constellation, bringing the exotic beauty of tropical birds to the night sky.

UMa.name: Ursa Major
UMa.description: The Great Bear from Greek mythology, a prominent and easily recognizable constellation.

UMi.name: Ursa Minor
UMi.description: The Little Bear, home to Polaris, the North Star, guiding travelers for millennia.

Vel.name: Vela
Vel.description: The sails of the ship Argo Navis, continuing the maritime mythological narrative.

Vir.name: Virgo
Vir.description: A maiden or virgin constellation, associated with the goddess Astraea, representing purity and justice.

Vol.name: Volans
Vol.description: A flying fish constellation, capturing the magic of marine life.

Vul.name: Vulpecula
Vul.description: A fox constellation, adding cunning and agility to the stellar menagerie.
